In article <1992Sep28.160834.5578@neptune.inf.ethz.ch>, I wrote
in connection with the RSA public key system:

|> The function returns the secret (private) exponent d which is
|> the multiplicative inverse of e in the finite field of numbers
|> in the range [0,(p-1)(q-1)-1].

Before anyone else points this out to me: the integers in the
range [0,(p-1)(q-1)-1] are of course not a field (since the
modulus is not a prime number) but only a ring.  However, e is
"constructed" in such a way that a multiplicative inverse modulo
(p-1)(q-1) exists.

